<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="205" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,319,2037]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,607,632]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Description:</emphasis>
Colour is beige alive and after fixation. The largest specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[1117,1217,607,632]" name="El Salvador" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Salvador</collectingCountry>
measures 1.2 x 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" unit="cm" value="2.1">2.1 cm</quantity>
(height x width) and has an irregular shape (
<figureCitation box="[689,809,644,669]" captionStart="FIGURE2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1808,1830]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,375,1786]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,375,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE2. Leucandra serrata (A, B, C, D, F: UFBA4525-POR; E: UFBA4658-POR).A—Preserved specimen with oscular membrane and fringe of trichoxeas (arrowhead); B—Oscular fringe; C—Longitudinal section with a general view of the skeleton (cx—cortex); D—Tangential section showing the cortical skeleton with triactines; E—Cross-section of a canal with apical actines of tetractines; F—Longitudinal section showing the atrium (at) with apical actines of tetractines (arrowhead)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098680/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figure 2A</figureCitation>
). The osculum is apical and has a membrane filled with spicules, to which several trichoxeas are inserted forming a fringe (
<figureCitation box="[928,1048,679,704]" captionStart="FIGURE2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1808,1830]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,375,1786]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,375,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE2. Leucandra serrata (A, B, C, D, F: UFBA4525-POR; E: UFBA4658-POR).A—Preserved specimen with oscular membrane and fringe of trichoxeas (arrowhead); B—Oscular fringe; C—Longitudinal section with a general view of the skeleton (cx—cortex); D—Tangential section showing the cortical skeleton with triactines; E—Cross-section of a canal with apical actines of tetractines; F—Longitudinal section showing the atrium (at) with apical actines of tetractines (arrowhead)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098680/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figure 2B</figureCitation>
). The surface of the specimens is undulated and hispid, with some diactines perforating the cortex. The body wall is 
<quantity box="[1106,1184,716,741]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" unit="cm" value="0.5">0.5 cm</quantity>
thick. The aquiferous system is leuconoid, with ovoid choanocyte chambers. The atrial cavity fills about half of the specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,319,2037]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">
The skeleton of the cortex is formed mainly by triactines of different shapes and sizes and by diactines that penetrate the cortex and extend until the choanosomal region (
<figureCitation box="[864,1031,823,848]" captionStart="FIGURE2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1808,1830]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,375,1786]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,375,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE2. Leucandra serrata (A, B, C, D, F: UFBA4525-POR; E: UFBA4658-POR).A—Preserved specimen with oscular membrane and fringe of trichoxeas (arrowhead); B—Oscular fringe; C—Longitudinal section with a general view of the skeleton (cx—cortex); D—Tangential section showing the cortical skeleton with triactines; E—Cross-section of a canal with apical actines of tetractines; F—Longitudinal section showing the atrium (at) with apical actines of tetractines (arrowhead)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098680/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figures 2C, D</figureCitation>
). Microdiactines are also present at the sponge surface (
<figureCitation box="[375,492,860,885]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1151,1173]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leucandra serrata (UFBA 4525-POR). A—Diactine; B—Jagged microdiactine; C—Cortical triactine; D— Choanosomal triactine; E—Tetractine of the canals; F—Atrial tetractine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098682/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figure 3B</figureCitation>
). The choanosomal skeleton is formed by large triactines arranged in a disorganised way (
<figureCitation box="[212,330,895,920]" captionStart="FIGURE2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1808,1830]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,375,1786]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,375,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE2. Leucandra serrata (A, B, C, D, F: UFBA4525-POR; E: UFBA4658-POR).A—Preserved specimen with oscular membrane and fringe of trichoxeas (arrowhead); B—Oscular fringe; C—Longitudinal section with a general view of the skeleton (cx—cortex); D—Tangential section showing the cortical skeleton with triactines; E—Cross-section of a canal with apical actines of tetractines; F—Longitudinal section showing the atrium (at) with apical actines of tetractines (arrowhead)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098680/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figure 2C</figureCitation>
). Additionally, we found tetractines around the canals, their apical actines facing the lumen (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1808,1830]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,375,1786]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,375,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE2. Leucandra serrata (A, B, C, D, F: UFBA4525-POR; E: UFBA4658-POR).A—Preserved specimen with oscular membrane and fringe of trichoxeas (arrowhead); B—Oscular fringe; C—Longitudinal section with a general view of the skeleton (cx—cortex); D—Tangential section showing the cortical skeleton with triactines; E—Cross-section of a canal with apical actines of tetractines; F—Longitudinal section showing the atrium (at) with apical actines of tetractines (arrowhead)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098680/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figure 2E</figureCitation>
). These spicules are smaller than the choanosomal triactines. The atrial skeleton is formed by tetractines with the apical actine projected to the atrium (
<figureCitation box="[609,724,967,992]" captionStart="FIGURE2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1808,1830]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,375,1786]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,375,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE2. Leucandra serrata (A, B, C, D, F: UFBA4525-POR; E: UFBA4658-POR).A—Preserved specimen with oscular membrane and fringe of trichoxeas (arrowhead); B—Oscular fringe; C—Longitudinal section with a general view of the skeleton (cx—cortex); D—Tangential section showing the cortical skeleton with triactines; E—Cross-section of a canal with apical actines of tetractines; F—Longitudinal section showing the atrium (at) with apical actines of tetractines (arrowhead)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098680/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figure 2F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,319,2037]" box="[199,926,1004,1029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,297,1004,1029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Spicules</emphasis>
(
<tableCitation box="[311,396,1004,1029]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,239,152,175]" captionText="TABLE 1. Spicule measurements of Leucandra serrata (UFBA 4525-POR and UFBA 4658-POR)." pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Table 1</tableCitation>
; measurements obtained from two specimens):
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,319,2037]" box="[199,843,1039,1064]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Trichoxeas: Very thin and long. Most of them are broken.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,319,2037]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">
Diactines: Fusiform and sharply pointed or with one of the tips blunt [478.8– 
<emphasis box="[1091,1168,1076,1100]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">1023.0</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1186,1201,1077,1100]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">±</emphasis>
287.5)–1769.0/15.9– 
<emphasis box="[151,200,1112,1136]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">42.8</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[216,231,1113,1136]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">±</emphasis>
12.4)–61.5 µm; 
<figureCitation box="[411,528,1111,1136]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1151,1173]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leucandra serrata (UFBA 4525-POR). A—Diactine; B—Jagged microdiactine; C—Cortical triactine; D— Choanosomal triactine; E—Tetractine of the canals; F—Atrial tetractine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098682/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figure 3A</figureCitation>
]
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,319,2037]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">
Microdiactines: Thin, slightly curved and jagged at one of the tips [71.3– 
<emphasis box="[1020,1083,1148,1172]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">107.6</emphasis>
(24.0)–170.2/2.1– 
<emphasis box="[1291,1326,1148,1172]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">4.3</emphasis>
(1.3)–7.0 µm; 
<figureCitation box="[202,317,1183,1208]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1151,1173]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leucandra serrata (UFBA 4525-POR). A—Diactine; B—Jagged microdiactine; C—Cortical triactine; D— Choanosomal triactine; E—Tetractine of the canals; F—Atrial tetractine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098682/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figure 3B</figureCitation>
)]
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,319,2037]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">
Cortical triactines: Cylindrical with blunt tips. The paired actines are commonly curved. They have the same size or are larger than the unpaired one [paired: 12.6– 
<emphasis box="[764,827,1256,1280]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">199.1</emphasis>
(48.5)–285.7/3.7– 
<emphasis box="[1037,1072,1256,1280]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">7.3</emphasis>
(2.1)–16.1 µm; unpaired: 42.9– 
<emphasis box="[151,214,1292,1316]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">131.1</emphasis>
(55.9)–288.7/3.9– 
<emphasis box="[429,464,1292,1316]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">8.0</emphasis>
(2.0)–14.3 µm; 
<figureCitation box="[646,764,1292,1317]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1151,1173]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leucandra serrata (UFBA 4525-POR). A—Diactine; B—Jagged microdiactine; C—Cortical triactine; D— Choanosomal triactine; E—Tetractine of the canals; F—Atrial tetractine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098682/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figure 3C</figureCitation>
].
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,319,2037]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">
Choanosomal triactines: Conical and sharp pointed. The size is variable, but they are the largest spicules present in the skeleton. The paired actines are slightly larger than the unpaired one and they are also sometimes slightly curved. In some cases, all actines have different sizes [paired: 177.3– 
<emphasis box="[1082,1145,1400,1424]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">490.5</emphasis>
(198.7)–948.9/14.5– 
<emphasis box="[1387,1436,1400,1424]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">37.4</emphasis>
(13.8)–65.5 µm; unpaired: 128.0– 
<emphasis box="[530,593,1436,1460]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">352.1</emphasis>
(133.4)–667.0/15.1– 
<emphasis box="[829,878,1436,1460]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">38.3</emphasis>
(15.1)–67.7 µm; 
<figureCitation box="[1074,1192,1436,1461]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1151,1173]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leucandra serrata (UFBA 4525-POR). A—Diactine; B—Jagged microdiactine; C—Cortical triactine; D— Choanosomal triactine; E—Tetractine of the canals; F—Atrial tetractine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098682/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figure 3D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,319,2037]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">
Choanosomal tetractines (canals): Conical with sharp tips. Some spicules have a slight undulation close to the end of one of the paired actines. The unpaired actine is smaller than the paired ones. The apical actine is short [paired: 107.5– 
<emphasis box="[327,390,1544,1568]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">210.4</emphasis>
(46.2)–310.0/4.8– 
<emphasis box="[604,653,1544,1568]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">10.9</emphasis>
(3.0)–18.2 µm; unpaired: 84.1– 
<emphasis box="[1032,1095,1544,1568]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">184.2</emphasis>
(42.4)–279.2/7.4– 
<emphasis box="[1309,1353,1544,1568]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">11.6</emphasis>
(2.7)– 21.2 µm; apical: 17.0– 
<emphasis box="[410,459,1580,1604]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">42.4</emphasis>
(14.5)–86.2/4.5– 
<emphasis box="[653,688,1580,1604]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">8.2</emphasis>
(2.1)–15.9 µm; 
<figureCitation box="[870,986,1580,1605]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1151,1173]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leucandra serrata (UFBA 4525-POR). A—Diactine; B—Jagged microdiactine; C—Cortical triactine; D— Choanosomal triactine; E—Tetractine of the canals; F—Atrial tetractine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098682/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figure 3E</figureCitation>
].
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,319,2037]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">
Atrial tetractines: Cylindrical and with sharp tips. Paired actines are slightly curved and long, being larger than the other actines. The apical is short but sometimes it is larger than the unpaired actine (paired: 122.3– 
<emphasis box="[1373,1436,1652,1676]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">243.5</emphasis>
(32.9)–303.8/5.0– 
<emphasis box="[352,387,1688,1712]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">8.6</emphasis>
(2.2)–13.6 µm; unpaired: 50.4– 
<emphasis box="[755,818,1688,1712]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">100.6</emphasis>
(24.6)–195.7/4.3– 
<emphasis box="[1029,1064,1688,1712]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">9.3</emphasis>
(2.2)–14.5 µm; apical: 9.5– 
<emphasis box="[1387,1436,1688,1712]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">58.4</emphasis>
(22.5)–110.7/4.0– 
<emphasis box="[351,386,1724,1748]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">8.0</emphasis>
(2.2)–14.3µm; 
<figureCitation box="[561,676,1724,1749]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1151,1173]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1129]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leucandra serrata (UFBA 4525-POR). A—Diactine; B—Jagged microdiactine; C—Cortical triactine; D— Choanosomal triactine; E—Tetractine of the canals; F—Atrial tetractine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1098682/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Figure 3F</figureCitation>
].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="205" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,319,2037]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,299,1759,1784]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Ecology.</emphasis>
The artificial substrates where the specimens were sampled remained immersed for 2 months, so this is the maximum age of the sponges. Tunicates, bryozoans and demosponges, as well as macroalgae, were also among the colonisers. Considering the bathymetric distribution, it seems that 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Azevedo &amp; Klautau" authorityYear="2007" box="[1015,1125,1833,1856]" class="Calcarea" family="Grantiidae" genus="Leucandra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="serrata">
<emphasis box="[1015,1125,1833,1856]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">L. serrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is from very shallow water, as, to our knowledge, it occurs from 
<quantity box="[560,653,1868,1892]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" unit="m" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1 to 3 m</quantity>
in depth (
<bibRefCitation author="Azevedo" box="[764,1055,1868,1893]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" refString="Azevedo, F. &amp; Klautau, M. (2007) Calcareous sponges (Porifera, Calcarea) from Ilha Grande Bay, Brazil, with descriptions of three new species. Zootaxa, 1402 (1), 1 - 22. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1402.1.1" type="journal article" year="2007">Azevedo &amp; Klautau 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lanna" box="[1067,1264,1868,1892]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" refString="Lanna, E., Cavalcanti, F. F., Cardoso, L., Muricy, G. &amp; Klautau, M. (2009) Taxonomy of calcareous sponges (Porifera, Calcarea) from Potiguar Basin, NE Brazil. Zootaxa, 1973, 1 - 27." type="journal article" year="2009">
Lanna 
<emphasis box="[1143,1199,1868,1892]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
; current work).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="206" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,319,2037]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1903,1928]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Azevedo &amp; Klautau" authorityYear="2007" box="[324,537,1904,1928]" class="Calcarea" family="Grantiidae" genus="Leucandra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="serrata">
<emphasis box="[324,537,1904,1928]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Leucandra serrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described at the coast of Angra dos Reis, 
<collectingRegion box="[1207,1375,1903,1928]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
state (
<bibRefCitation author="Azevedo" box="[158,457,1940,1965]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" refString="Azevedo, F. &amp; Klautau, M. (2007) Calcareous sponges (Porifera, Calcarea) from Ilha Grande Bay, Brazil, with descriptions of three new species. Zootaxa, 1402 (1), 1 - 22. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1402.1.1" type="journal article" year="2007">Azevedo &amp; Klautau 2007</bibRefCitation>
) and was subsequently recorded 
<quantity box="[840,948,1940,1965]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" unit="km" value="2.9">2.900 km</quantity>
away, in the Potiguar Basin, Northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[151,219,1976,2001]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Muricy" box="[234,447,1976,2001]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" refString="Muricy, G., Esteves, E. L., Moraes, F. C., Santos, J. P., Silva, S. M., Almeida, E. V. R., Klautau, M. &amp; Lanna, E. (2008) Biodiversidade Marinha da Bacia Potiguar: Porifera. Museu Nacional, Rio de Janeiro, 156 pp." type="book" year="2008">
Muricy 
<emphasis box="[325,381,1976,2000]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lanna" box="[458,659,1976,2000]" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" refString="Lanna, E., Cavalcanti, F. F., Cardoso, L., Muricy, G. &amp; Klautau, M. (2009) Taxonomy of calcareous sponges (Porifera, Calcarea) from Potiguar Basin, NE Brazil. Zootaxa, 1973, 1 - 27." type="journal article" year="2009">
Lanna 
<emphasis box="[535,591,1976,2000]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
). The presence of this species in the coast of 
<collectingRegion box="[1162,1227,1976,2001]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Bahia</collectingRegion>
fills a large gap in the distribution of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Azevedo &amp; Klautau" authorityYear="2007" box="[358,469,2013,2036]" class="Calcarea" family="Grantiidae" genus="Leucandra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="2" pageNumber="205" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="serrata">
<emphasis box="[358,469,2013,2036]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">L. serrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
along the Brazilian coast, as 
<collectingRegion box="[798,863,2012,2037]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="2" pageNumber="205">Bahia</collectingRegion>
is between those localities.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">
The specimens described here have jagged microdiactines, long diactines in the cortex and large triactines at the choanosomal region, which are characteristics mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Azevedo" box="[912,1231,188,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="206" refString="Azevedo, F. &amp; Klautau, M. (2007) Calcareous sponges (Porifera, Calcarea) from Ilha Grande Bay, Brazil, with descriptions of three new species. Zootaxa, 1402 (1), 1 - 22. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1402.1.1" type="journal article" year="2007">Azevedo &amp; Klautau (2007)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation pageId="3" pageNumber="206" refString="Lanna, E., Cavalcanti, F. F., Cardoso, L., Muricy, G. &amp; Klautau, M. (2009) Taxonomy of calcareous sponges (Porifera, Calcarea) from Potiguar Basin, NE Brazil. Zootaxa, 1973, 1 - 27." type="journal article">
Lanna 
<emphasis box="[1375,1436,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
(2009)
</bibRefCitation>
for 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Azevedo &amp; Klautau" authorityYear="2007" box="[276,388,225,248]" class="Calcarea" family="Grantiidae" genus="Leucandra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="3" pageNumber="206" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="serrata">
<emphasis box="[276,388,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">L. serrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The only difference is the size of the choanosomal triactines: in the specimens from 
<collectingRegion box="[1371,1436,223,248]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">Bahia</collectingRegion>
they are larger (318.9– 
<emphasis box="[423,486,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">625.0</emphasis>
(185.5)–948.9/49.0 (8.7) µm) than those from the Potiguar Basin (156.0– 
<emphasis box="[1373,1436,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">294.0</emphasis>
(63.9)–426/26.8 (6.0) µm) and from 
<collectingRegion box="[562,724,295,320]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
(234.0– 
<emphasis box="[817,880,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">420.0</emphasis>
(69.0)–523.0/30.0 (6.0) µm).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
